00:00:28.302 --> 00:00:30.578
introduction, or the existence
theorem introductions

00:00:30.578 --> 00:00:31.890
on Khan Academy.

00:00:31.890 --> 00:00:33.434
But as a review for those of you

00:00:33.434 --> 00:00:35.686
who are familiar with
the mean value theorem,

00:00:35.686 --> 00:00:37.126
the conditions are,

00:00:37.126 --> 00:00:39.564
if we're dealing with some closed interval

00:00:39.564 --> 00:00:40.564
from a to b,

00:00:41.526 --> 00:00:44.034
we have to be differentiable,

00:00:44.034 --> 00:00:45.474
all right, just diff,

00:00:45.474 --> 00:00:46.945
actually, I'll just write it out,

00:00:46.945 --> 00:00:48.112
differentiable

00:00:50.625 --> 00:00:54.294
over the open interval from a to b,

00:00:54.294 --> 00:00:56.627
and we have to be continuous

00:00:58.381 --> 00:01:01.464
over the closed interval from a to b.

00:01:03.269 --> 00:01:04.151
Or another way to think about it,

00:01:04.151 --> 00:01:05.045
if you're differentiable,

00:01:05.045 --> 00:01:06.903
you're definitely going to be continuous.

00:01:06.903 --> 00:01:09.747
So, this second condition,

00:01:09.747 --> 00:01:11.465
just make sure that we're continuous

00:01:11.465 --> 00:01:14.578
at the endpoints of our closed interval.

00:01:14.578 --> 00:01:17.219
But if these conditions are met,

00:01:17.219 --> 00:01:19.377
then the mean value theorem tells us,

00:01:19.377 --> 00:01:20.479
and I'll just visually draw it

00:01:20.479 --> 00:01:22.245
because this is a review here.

00:01:22.245 --> 00:01:25.495
So let's say that this is our function.

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:29.156
So let's say our function looks like this,

00:01:29.156 --> 00:01:31.616
this is a and this is b,

00:01:31.616 --> 00:01:33.322
and let's say that we
meet these conditions

00:01:33.322 --> 00:01:34.454
over this interval,

00:01:34.454 --> 00:01:37.095
the mean value theorem tells us

00:01:37.095 --> 00:01:39.993
that there's going to be some value,

00:01:39.993 --> 00:01:41.849
let's call it c, in the interval,

00:01:41.849 --> 00:01:46.015
where the derivative of c is equal

00:01:46.015 --> 00:01:49.064
to the average rate of change from a to b.

00:01:49.064 --> 00:01:50.769
So the slope of the secant line

00:01:50.769 --> 00:01:53.018
is the average rate of change.

00:01:53.018 --> 00:01:54.286
And so you can see it visually,

00:01:54.286 --> 00:01:55.931
it looks like right about there,

00:01:55.931 --> 00:01:58.421
the slope of the tangent
line would be the same.

00:01:58.421 --> 00:02:01.108
And so this would be the c that exists.

00:02:01.108 --> 00:02:04.036
Now, in this video, we're not
trying to identify the c's,

00:02:04.036 --> 00:02:04.987
we're just trying to say,

00:02:04.987 --> 00:02:07.130
can we apply the mean value theorem?

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:08.368
So let's look at this first interval

00:02:08.368 --> 00:02:11.031
from negative five to negative
one, a closed interval.

00:02:11.031 --> 00:02:15.257
So we're going from negative
five to negative one.

00:02:15.257 --> 00:02:18.895
So are we differentiable
over the interval,

00:02:18.895 --> 00:02:20.615
over the open interval?

00:02:20.615 --> 00:02:23.483
We have this discontinuity over here

00:02:23.483 --> 00:02:25.264
that's not going to
make it differentiable,

00:02:25.264 --> 00:02:26.546
and, of course, this is also,

00:02:26.546 --> 00:02:28.297
if we're not continuous, we're not going

00:02:28.297 --> 00:02:30.108
to be differentiable here.

00:02:30.108 --> 00:02:32.236
So this discontinuity here

00:02:32.236 --> 00:02:34.772
actually violates both
of these conditions.

00:02:34.772 --> 00:02:37.368
And so for this first
interval, we would say, no,

00:02:37.368 --> 00:02:40.733
the mean value theorem does not apply.

00:02:40.733 --> 00:02:44.024
Now, the second one, from
negative one to three.

00:02:44.024 --> 00:02:45.774
So I'll do this in a
slightly different color.

00:02:45.774 --> 00:02:48.778
So we're gonna go from
